Let me reconsider. The Rust raw string r#"..."# will contain the C++ code, hiding it from Rust. For C++, that C++ code must be live. So the C++ code must NOT be in a C++ comment. But the lines `const _X: &str = r#"` and `"#;` must be hidden from C++.

Use `#if 0`/`#endif` to hide the Rust raw-string-delimiter lines from C++, while those `#if 0` lines themselves are inside the Rust raw string (hidden from Rust). Combined with backslash trick to bootstrap.

Final design:
Line1: `// \`  -> C++: comments line1+line2. Rust: comment line1.
Line2: `const _X: &str = r#"` -> Rust opens raw string. C++ ignores (continued comment).
Now inside Rust raw string (lines 3+), put: `#if 0` ... but wait these are in the raw string so Rust ignores, but C++ — C++ is NOT in the raw string concept; C++ sees these as normal lines. So `#if 0` is processed by C++.
We want C++ to skip the line that closes the raw string. So:
```
